WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:13.720
Today, we want to talk about self-service analytics and our new product, RStudio Connect

00:00:13.720 --> 00:00:15.280
that we released.

00:00:15.280 --> 00:00:17.520
We did a soft launch earlier this year.

00:00:17.520 --> 00:00:21.360
You can download an evaluation at any time.

00:00:21.360 --> 00:00:24.299
Hopefully some people that are in attendance today have seen it.

00:00:24.299 --> 00:00:30.500
We want to give you an explanation of why RStudio Connect and the value we think it

00:00:30.500 --> 00:00:35.299
adds to organizations and how to get the most out of it.

00:00:35.299 --> 00:00:41.020
I will walk through a few background slides and talk about our product stack a little

00:00:41.020 --> 00:00:42.020
bit.

00:00:42.020 --> 00:00:47.580
If you are familiar with RStudio IDE, we will talk about the packages a little bit.

00:00:47.580 --> 00:00:54.820
They tie all of these things together, specifically Shiny and RMarkdown and also the Tidyverse

00:00:54.820 --> 00:00:59.220
and our new product, RStudio Connect.

00:00:59.220 --> 00:01:01.220
First I want to cover the Tidyverse.

00:01:01.220 --> 00:01:04.779
If you have not seen the Tidyverse, it is a collection of R packages that share common

00:01:04.779 --> 00:01:07.699
philosophies and are designed to work together.

00:01:07.699 --> 00:01:12.419
These are a lot of packages that Hadley's team has put together or worked on.

00:01:12.419 --> 00:01:18.019
You can read about them in R for Data Science, which is a book that Hadley and Garrett wrote.

00:01:18.019 --> 00:01:19.019
It is free.

00:01:19.019 --> 00:01:22.860
It is online or you can buy it through a publisher if you would like.

00:01:22.860 --> 00:01:28.379
The Tidyverse can be installed and loaded very easily just by including Tidyverse.

00:01:28.379 --> 00:01:32.940
What happens is it will load up all of these packages that you see on your screen.

00:01:32.940 --> 00:01:38.540
The idea of the Tidyverse is that you will be using these to create analyses and visualizations

00:01:38.540 --> 00:01:41.820
and do your work in a very fluid way.

00:01:42.220 --> 00:01:49.459
That is what I want to talk about next, this process of doing analytics.

00:01:49.459 --> 00:01:56.860
Most people have some set of data that they start with and they import that data and clean

00:01:56.860 --> 00:01:58.940
it up and try to understand their data.

00:01:58.940 --> 00:02:05.139
They go through a cycle of transforming, visualizing, and modeling their data.

00:02:05.139 --> 00:02:09.220
When you are done with that, you want to communicate what you learned to other people.

00:02:09.619 --> 00:02:12.740
You want to share the insights and understandings with people.

00:02:12.740 --> 00:02:19.500
That often involves publishing either some sort of documentation or visualization or

00:02:19.500 --> 00:02:22.220
application.

00:02:22.220 --> 00:02:26.539
This workflow here, this process workflow of programming and data science, is the way

00:02:26.539 --> 00:02:32.220
we conceptualize doing data science with R. This is what the R for Data Science book is

00:02:32.220 --> 00:02:38.020
a lot of what it is about, is managing this workflow and providing the tools to do this

00:02:38.020 --> 00:02:39.020
effectively.

00:02:39.020 --> 00:02:45.380
Today, we are going to be talking about this last part of the workflow, which is communicate.

00:02:45.380 --> 00:02:49.820
That is what we want to talk to you today about, is communicate.

00:02:49.820 --> 00:02:51.059
Communicating involves two parties.

00:02:51.059 --> 00:02:53.660
The first party is the content creator.

00:02:53.660 --> 00:02:54.660
Who is the content creator?

00:02:54.660 --> 00:02:59.419
That is the data scientists, the domain experts, or the app developers.

00:02:59.419 --> 00:03:06.580
Their job is to understand, measure, predict, and optimize systems and analyses on top of

00:03:06.580 --> 00:03:07.580
their data.

00:03:08.139 --> 00:03:14.619
The output of that understanding is typically artifacts, documents, applications, or plots

00:03:14.619 --> 00:03:15.619
or whatnot.

00:03:15.619 --> 00:03:19.380
Then you have the content consumers.

00:03:19.380 --> 00:03:23.660
These are the people that are the managers, the peers, maybe other students.

00:03:23.660 --> 00:03:29.779
These people may or may not understand R or have a great background in analytics.

00:03:29.779 --> 00:03:35.699
Their job is to take what you learn, what you do, and make decisions and take actions

00:03:36.020 --> 00:03:38.300
and see results.

00:03:38.300 --> 00:03:43.300
These content consumers are extremely important in taking advantage of the artifacts that

00:03:43.300 --> 00:03:44.300
are being created.

00:03:44.300 --> 00:03:50.500
A typical process workflow, and this is what I am very familiar with, I am an analyst by

00:03:50.500 --> 00:03:51.500
training.

00:03:51.500 --> 00:03:52.500
I have used R for a long time.

00:03:52.500 --> 00:03:57.380
I go into R and create my analysis.

00:03:57.380 --> 00:04:02.740
When I am done, I make a report and I send it on to the consumers by email or SharePoint

00:04:02.740 --> 00:04:06.220
or put it on the file share somewhere.

00:04:06.220 --> 00:04:09.380
That is a very traditional way of sharing your analysis.

00:04:09.380 --> 00:04:13.979
What happens when you do that, invariably, somebody asks a question.

00:04:13.979 --> 00:04:19.859
They say, there is an error here, or I want to see more, or I want to go deeper.

00:04:19.859 --> 00:04:26.459
The content creator goes back to work, opens up their code, and creates a new artifact.

00:04:26.459 --> 00:04:31.579
That artifact is then pushed back to the content consumers and the cycle repeats.

00:04:31.579 --> 00:04:33.980
This can be a time-consuming cycle.

00:04:33.980 --> 00:04:38.660
The question is, can we do better, can we be more efficient in the way that this cycle

00:04:38.660 --> 00:04:39.660
is managed?

00:04:39.660 --> 00:04:43.019
Yes, there are ways to make this better.

00:04:43.019 --> 00:04:46.579
One of those ways is to create something that might be self-service.

00:04:46.579 --> 00:04:53.339
Wouldn't it be great if instead of the content consumer asking the content creator a question,

00:04:53.339 --> 00:04:57.899
if they could go back to the artifact and ask that question and get the answer from

00:04:57.899 --> 00:04:59.420
the artifact itself?

00:05:00.260 --> 00:05:05.820
Wouldn't it also be great if you could schedule and distribute these reports without having

00:05:05.820 --> 00:05:09.019
to do it in a manual process?

00:05:09.019 --> 00:05:13.420
If you have a dashboard that you need updated every week, maybe the system can handle that.

00:05:13.420 --> 00:05:18.299
If you want to distribute one version of the report to one group and another version of

00:05:18.299 --> 00:05:21.299
the report to another group, maybe the system can handle that.

00:05:21.299 --> 00:05:26.700
Wouldn't it be great if all of this content just ran naturally and natively in R?

00:05:26.739 --> 00:05:31.859
That's the language that we know, so we want to be able to make sure that the system can

00:05:31.859 --> 00:05:38.179
run all of this natively in R, can serve up Shiny apps and R Markdown documents.

00:05:38.179 --> 00:05:44.179
And finally, wouldn't it be great if we can just pass much more of the control that we

00:05:44.179 --> 00:05:49.779
typically maintain in our daily work to the content consumers and allow those content

00:05:49.779 --> 00:05:55.339
consumers to have some of that control to get the answers that they need to run R, even

00:05:55.339 --> 00:06:02.660
if they don't know how to use R, to schedule the reports and take action on the analyses

00:06:02.660 --> 00:06:04.140
on their own?

00:06:04.140 --> 00:06:10.019
So that's what RStudio Connect is designed to handle.

00:06:10.019 --> 00:06:12.500
That's what we're going to be talking about next.

00:06:12.500 --> 00:06:17.179
So my colleague Sean is going to talk a little bit about these different types of artifacts.

00:06:17.179 --> 00:06:22.059
The first one is going to be this static document, right, where you just have a very basic R

00:06:22.059 --> 00:06:23.059
Markdown document.

00:06:23.339 --> 00:06:27.899
And then he's going to talk about parameterized documents and how powerful that those are.

00:06:27.899 --> 00:06:31.700
And then he's finally going to talk about application development, hosting applications

00:06:31.700 --> 00:06:37.779
in a way that consumers can take control of those applications.

00:06:37.779 --> 00:06:40.380
So I don't want to take any more time away from the demos.

00:06:40.380 --> 00:06:43.820
Let's dive in and see what we have.

00:06:43.820 --> 00:06:48.899
And I will pass the baton over to Sean then.

00:06:48.899 --> 00:06:52.220
So thanks for that introduction, Nathan.

00:06:52.380 --> 00:06:56.339
What we're going to be talking about today, just as Nathan said, is how to get that control

00:06:56.339 --> 00:07:01.260
over to the end users and make your lives as data scientists a bit easier.

00:07:01.260 --> 00:07:05.540
And we're going to be doing that with content, and content has to have a data source.

00:07:05.540 --> 00:07:11.179
So our data source today is going to be this Star Wars API, or SWAPI for short.

00:07:11.179 --> 00:07:12.660
It's a great data set.

00:07:12.660 --> 00:07:15.660
It's a lot of fun if you're a Star Wars fan like me.

